ij argues, are not only (re)productions of local and personal contextuality, but are co-dependent and co-productive to the reports themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamxPress coveragezGreat Britain. 0aMuslimsxPublic opinionzGreat Britain. 0aMuslimszGreat BritainxPublic opinion. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aAudience Reception Study.  aContent Analysis.  aDiscourse Analysis.  aHermeneutics.  aIslam.  aMedia.  aMuslims.  aNewspapers.  aNon-Muslims.  aTelevision.1 ade Rooij, Laurens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613523040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526135230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526135230/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles